00:06:34.980 --> 00:06:38.015
is the diagnoses that I have.

00:06:38.015 --> 00:06:40.090
I have two things that
I've been diagnosed with.

00:06:40.090 --> 00:06:42.280
One is generalized
anxiety disorder.

00:06:42.280 --> 00:06:47.745
And the ones that I tend to tell
people my experience with it

00:06:47.745 --> 00:06:50.770
is that I have fight or
flight reactions when

00:06:50.770 --> 00:06:52.820
it's not appropriate.

00:06:52.820 --> 00:06:56.090
It is appropriate to have a
fight or flight reaction when

00:06:56.090 --> 00:06:57.740
my life is in danger.

00:06:57.740 --> 00:07:01.250
If there is a lion
that's going to attack me

00:07:01.250 --> 00:07:05.450
and I need to either run away
or roundhouse kick this lion,

00:07:05.450 --> 00:07:08.030
that is an appropriate time
to have a fight or flight

00:07:08.030 --> 00:07:09.020
reaction.

00:07:09.020 --> 00:07:10.820
My brain says, you
need to be in this mode

00:07:10.820 --> 00:07:13.040
because you might need
to beat up something

00:07:13.040 --> 00:07:15.470
or you might need to run
as fast as hell to get away

00:07:15.470 --> 00:07:18.650
from this thing to survive.

00:07:18.650 --> 00:07:21.421
That is an appropriate time
your brain tells your whole body

00:07:21.421 --> 00:07:21.920
to kick in.

00:07:21.920 --> 00:07:24.920
Your physiology changes.

00:07:24.920 --> 00:07:28.370
Hormones and chemicals start
pumping through your system.

00:07:28.370 --> 00:07:29.460
Lots of stuff happens.

00:07:29.460 --> 00:07:32.240
Physiology dramatically
shift from a normal state

00:07:32.240 --> 00:07:33.840
to a high stress state.

00:07:33.840 --> 00:07:38.330
And it changes because it
is a survival mechanism.

00:07:38.330 --> 00:07:42.500
It is not appropriate to have
a fight or flight reaction when

00:07:42.500 --> 00:07:45.950
you're going to meet friends at
a bar that you've never been to

00:07:45.950 --> 00:07:48.610
and you're standing
outside, and you're

00:07:48.610 --> 00:07:50.980
so uncomfortable with the
idea of going into this place

00:07:50.980 --> 00:07:52.690
and you're not sure exactly
where they're sitting

00:07:52.690 --> 00:07:54.731
and you don't really know
what it's like in there

00:07:54.731 --> 00:07:57.070
and what's the layout like
and you just get freaked out,

00:07:57.070 --> 00:07:59.572
and you decide that maybe I
should just go back to my car

00:07:59.572 --> 00:08:01.030
and sit in my car
for a few minutes

00:08:01.030 --> 00:08:04.700
and then just
drive home instead.

00:08:04.700 --> 00:08:07.650
That has happened
to me many times.

00:08:07.650 --> 00:08:10.560
That's happened
to me many times.

00:08:10.560 --> 00:08:13.470
It's not appropriate
to have it where you're

00:08:13.470 --> 00:08:16.320
afraid to take the bus or other
kinds of public transportation

00:08:16.320 --> 00:08:18.870
because you don't understand
the payment system

00:08:18.870 --> 00:08:22.525
and you're so afraid of being
embarrassed, of standing up

00:08:22.525 --> 00:08:24.900
and people being mad at you
because you're slowing things

00:08:24.900 --> 00:08:26.940
down and stuff like that.

00:08:26.940 --> 00:08:28.680
I just don't ever take those.

00:08:28.680 --> 00:08:29.760
I don't take the bus.

00:08:29.760 --> 00:08:30.701
I don't take trains.

00:08:30.701 --> 00:08:31.200
It helps.

00:08:31.200 --> 00:08:33.340
I don't live in Chicago
so there's less of that,

00:08:33.340 --> 00:08:36.380
but there are at least
buses where I live.

00:08:36.380 --> 00:08:40.559
And that is not an
appropriate time

00:08:40.559 --> 00:08:42.039
to have those kind of reactions.

00:08:42.039 --> 00:08:44.860
But I do.

00:08:44.860 --> 00:08:46.537
I do have those
kinds of reactions

00:08:46.537 --> 00:08:48.370
in those situations,
particularly situations

00:08:48.370 --> 00:08:51.040
where I feel like I don't
understand the rules

00:08:51.040 --> 00:08:54.250
or like I'm not competent
enough to handle this.

00:08:54.250 --> 00:08:56.140
I get very, very
deeply uncomfortable.

00:08:56.140 --> 00:08:58.780
My brain says something's
wrong, and you

00:08:58.780 --> 00:09:01.870
have to protect yourself.

00:09:01.870 --> 00:09:04.330
It tells me that very loudly.

00:09:04.330 --> 00:09:11.705
I also have ADHD, attention
deficit hyperactivity disorder.

00:09:11.705 --> 00:09:13.830
And that's something that
gets thrown around a lot.

00:09:13.830 --> 00:09:15.420
A lot of people kind of
talk about that stuff.

00:09:15.420 --> 00:09:17.920
And there's some things that
are kind of typical that you're

00:09:17.920 --> 00:09:19.380
used to that go along with ADHD.

00:09:19.380 --> 00:09:21.480
And my experiences
with it, a lot of them

00:09:21.480 --> 00:09:25.290
are similar, that as an
adult, I have trouble

00:09:25.290 --> 00:09:26.720
focusing on single tasks.

00:09:26.720 --> 00:09:29.220
So I often jump from one
thing to another a lot.

00:09:29.220 --> 00:09:31.380
I also tend to avoid.

00:09:31.380 --> 00:09:34.020
Avoidance is a whole
big thing, a big part

00:09:34.020 --> 00:09:36.840
of my life that
I've struggled with,

00:09:36.840 --> 00:09:39.560
avoidance of unappealing tasks.

00:09:39.560 --> 00:09:41.910
And it's not stuff like,
well, you know, I don't really

00:09:41.910 --> 00:09:45.060
feel like doing this right
now, but I'll get around to it.

00:09:45.060 --> 00:09:49.320
It's been more like, yeah,
I will just never do that

00:09:49.320 --> 00:09:51.379
and my water will get
shut off because I just

00:09:51.379 --> 00:09:52.920
didn't get around
to paying the bills

00:09:52.920 --> 00:09:53.880
because I kept forgetting.

00:09:53.880 --> 00:09:56.255
And when I did do it, I was
like, I really don't want to.

00:09:56.255 --> 00:09:59.880
I feel strangely like almost
almost anxious about it

00:09:59.880 --> 00:10:00.630
and uncomfortable.

00:10:00.630 --> 00:10:02.040
It's like I don't want to
deal with that right now.

00:10:02.040 --> 00:10:03.480
I've had that happen.

00:10:03.480 --> 00:10:05.976
I have the money.

00:10:05.976 --> 00:10:07.100
I just didn't pay the bill.

00:10:09.560 --> 00:10:11.060
But there's a couple
of other things

00:10:11.060 --> 00:10:15.241
that often go hand-in-hand with
ADHD and the kind of stuff I

00:10:15.241 --> 00:10:15.740
deal with.

00:10:15.740 --> 00:10:19.544
And one of those
things is oftentimes,

00:10:19.544 --> 00:10:20.960
I have these two
different things,

00:10:20.960 --> 00:10:22.168
but they sort of go together.

00:10:22.168 --> 00:10:26.760
I have what I usually say is
a low frustration threshold.

00:10:26.760 --> 00:10:29.550
And this is fairly common
with people with ADHD,

00:10:29.550 --> 00:10:31.510
that they often get
frustrated quickly,

00:10:31.510 --> 00:10:35.970
especially if the way they
expect things to go changes

00:10:35.970 --> 00:10:38.090
rather suddenly.

00:10:38.090 --> 00:10:40.110
Most people aren't super
comfortable with that,

00:10:40.110 --> 00:10:42.020
but they can adapt OK.

00:10:42.020 --> 00:10:45.850
I have a very strong
emotional reaction to that,

00:10:45.850 --> 00:10:48.140
oftentimes very--

00:10:48.140 --> 00:10:52.520
and I think it ties in with an
idea that I feel uncomfortable

00:10:52.520 --> 00:10:54.370
and I tend to get angry
in those situations.

00:10:54.370 --> 00:10:55.580
I get frustrated.

00:10:55.580 --> 00:10:58.820
Or I get very frustrated when
it feels like I'm just not

00:10:58.820 --> 00:11:01.460
capable of doing something
and I get frustrated much more

00:11:01.460 --> 00:11:04.390
quickly than seems normal
to the people around me,

00:11:04.390 --> 00:11:07.700
than what seems like the norm.

00:11:07.700 --> 00:11:10.550
The intensity of my emotions
is often much stronger

00:11:10.550 --> 00:11:13.130
than it seems like it
is for other people.

00:11:13.130 --> 00:11:15.830
Sometimes it feels like my
emotions are out of control

00:11:15.830 --> 00:11:18.125
despite the fact that
I know logically I

00:11:18.125 --> 00:11:20.330
am having a reaction
that is not in line

00:11:20.330 --> 00:11:23.170
with the severity
of the situation.

00:11:23.170 --> 00:11:25.340
I know that.

00:11:25.340 --> 00:11:33.020
And yet I don't know how to turn
off that fire hose of emotion

00:11:33.020 --> 00:11:34.310
that sometimes comes over me.

00:11:34.310 --> 00:11:37.730
And sometimes I just have to
sequester myself off and wait

00:11:37.730 --> 00:11:40.820
until it calms down because
otherwise I will say and do

00:11:40.820 --> 00:11:43.310
things that are destructive.

00:11:43.310 --> 00:11:46.550
I'll hurt people
around me that I love.

00:11:46.550 --> 00:11:50.860
Emotionally I will act out
in different kinds of ways.

00:11:53.430 --> 00:11:57.030
I'm also particularly good
at constructing bad outcomes

00:11:57.030 --> 00:11:59.740
and hyperfocusing on them.

00:11:59.740 --> 00:12:01.930
So an example would be--

00:12:01.930 --> 00:12:04.630
this happened to
me more than once.

00:12:04.630 --> 00:12:07.560
I've got an email
from the person

00:12:07.560 --> 00:12:12.190
who is my manager,
my boss, and said--

00:12:12.190 --> 00:12:15.570
hey, could you-- it's like
a Friday, late on Friday.

00:12:15.570 --> 00:12:18.030
Hey, on Monday could you
come in and we could talk?

00:12:20.540 --> 00:12:22.880
OK, all right, well
what's going to happen?

00:12:22.880 --> 00:12:23.862
Oh, this is alarming.

00:12:23.862 --> 00:12:25.070
I don't know what's going on.

00:12:25.070 --> 00:12:26.820
Maybe he knew about
that thing that I did.

00:12:26.820 --> 00:12:29.210
Was that thing--
oh my gosh, oh no.

00:12:29.210 --> 00:12:34.610
And I would construct a scenario
where I'm losing my job.

00:12:34.610 --> 00:12:36.170
We won't have any income.

00:12:36.170 --> 00:12:40.670
I will be so shamed that
my family will abandon me.

00:12:40.670 --> 00:12:41.720
We will lose our house.

00:12:41.720 --> 00:12:42.980
I will be homeless.

00:12:42.980 --> 00:12:44.090
My career is shot.

00:12:44.090 --> 00:12:47.570
I will have nothing to live for.

00:12:47.570 --> 00:12:49.520
And I will live the
next couple of days

00:12:49.520 --> 00:12:52.550
unable to put that aside, unable
to take that out of my brain

00:12:52.550 --> 00:12:54.300
and say, you know what,
that's ridiculous.

00:12:54.300 --> 00:12:56.030
It's probably not
something like that.

00:12:56.030 --> 00:12:58.550
Everything's going to be OK.

00:12:58.550 --> 00:13:02.540
I want to tell myself that,
but it doesn't work that way.

00:13:02.540 --> 00:13:04.700
Those emotions are
so strong and I'm

00:13:04.700 --> 00:13:06.920
so good at constructing
those outcomes

00:13:06.920 --> 00:13:09.230
and I have very
detailed lists of that.

00:13:09.230 --> 00:13:14.090
And I live as if that is then
the predetermined outcome.

00:13:14.090 --> 00:13:20.970
And I get in on Monday and
my boss says, "So how's

00:13:20.970 --> 00:13:22.086
that project going?"

00:13:22.086 --> 00:13:23.640
I'm like, "Oh, it's good.

00:13:23.640 --> 00:13:26.300
Actually we finished that up.

00:13:26.300 --> 00:13:27.690
Yeah, that was really good."

00:13:27.690 --> 00:13:29.640
And meanwhile there's
sweat pouring off.

00:13:29.640 --> 00:13:32.883
And I'm like, [BREATHS HEAVILY]

00:13:33.383 --> 00:13:34.856
[EXHALES]

00:13:35.840 --> 00:13:38.090
And it's like an
elephant has been sitting

00:13:38.090 --> 00:13:40.280
on my chest for the
past three days,

00:13:40.280 --> 00:13:43.390
and suddenly it just got off.

00:13:43.390 --> 00:13:45.875
And there really wasn't
anything to worry about.

00:13:45.875 --> 00:13:48.250
But I'm really, really good
at constructing those things,

00:13:48.250 --> 00:13:49.700
really, really good at that.

00:13:49.700 --> 00:13:50.860
So how do I deal with it?

00:13:50.860 --> 00:13:53.970
I take medication is
one thing that I do.

00:13:53.970 --> 00:13:57.590
I take about five
different things every day.

00:13:57.590 --> 00:13:59.030
And that's something that helps.

00:13:59.030 --> 00:14:02.300
And I've been dealing
with this 30 years.

00:14:02.300 --> 00:14:05.314
And right now that's
the kind of cocktail

00:14:05.314 --> 00:14:07.730
that works for me that helps
kind of keep myself in check.

00:14:07.730 --> 00:14:08.438
It's not perfect.

00:14:08.438 --> 00:14:10.560
It doesn't mean that
I never have symptoms,

00:14:10.560 --> 00:14:12.419
but they're a lot less severe.

00:14:12.419 --> 00:14:14.210
And I also see a
therapist every two weeks.

00:14:14.210 --> 00:14:18.600
And I talk about what's
happened with me, why

00:14:18.600 --> 00:14:21.210
I do the things that I do, try
to break down those scenarios,

00:14:21.210 --> 00:14:23.501
try to break down sort of
the process of that behavior.

00:14:23.501 --> 00:14:25.970
We go through thing a called
cognitive behavioral therapy,

00:14:25.970 --> 00:14:28.303
which is a common thing that's
used with a lot of people

00:14:28.303 --> 00:14:30.870
with anxiety disorders
that's pretty effective,

00:14:30.870 --> 00:14:33.450
and talk about how and
why I do the things I do

00:14:33.450 --> 00:14:36.211
and come up with
strategies to address that.

00:14:36.211 --> 00:14:38.710
Basically like kind of having
a coach for your brain instead

00:14:38.710 --> 00:14:41.290
of somebody who's telling
you to do sit-ups.

00:14:41.290 --> 00:14:43.560
That's how it is
with my therapist.

00:14:43.560 --> 00:14:45.130
Your therapist
could be different.

00:14:45.130 --> 00:14:46.796
But that's how it
kind of works with me.

00:14:49.740 --> 00:14:51.400
And those things help.

00:14:51.400 --> 00:14:53.370
And I've gotten
better at things.

00:14:53.370 --> 00:14:55.800
Stuff used to be a lot worse.

00:14:55.800 --> 00:14:57.810
It's gotten better.

00:14:57.810 --> 00:14:59.580
It impacts my work every day.

00:14:59.580 --> 00:15:02.490
Every single day I am
living with my brain.

00:15:02.490 --> 00:15:05.490
And the work that I do involves
thinking and solving problems

00:15:05.490 --> 00:15:06.720
and figuring stuff out.

00:15:06.720 --> 00:15:10.200
And things that affect the
way that my brain processes

00:15:10.200 --> 00:15:14.900
work are pretty serious,
that affects my thinking

00:15:14.900 --> 00:15:19.070
are particularly problematic,
potentially at least.

00:15:19.070 --> 00:15:21.120
Now sometimes it
gives me superpowers,

00:15:21.120 --> 00:15:23.340
absolutely gives
me super powers.

00:15:23.340 --> 00:15:26.220
I'm really good at
certain aspects of my job

00:15:26.220 --> 00:15:27.870
because of the way
my brain works.

00:15:27.870 --> 00:15:30.970
I'm really good at constructing
negative outcomes, really good

00:15:30.970 --> 00:15:31.470
at that.

00:15:31.470 --> 00:15:33.803
I'm actually really good at
constructing outcomes period

00:15:33.803 --> 00:15:36.440
and figuring out,
well, if we do this,

00:15:36.440 --> 00:15:38.610
how is that going to impact
our system over here?

00:15:38.610 --> 00:15:40.110
If we do this thing
in the back end,

00:15:40.110 --> 00:15:42.240
how's that going to impact
how a user has to interact

00:15:42.240 --> 00:15:43.323
with our system over here?

00:15:46.040 --> 00:15:48.290
I tend to be kind of good
at anticipating security

00:15:48.290 --> 00:15:49.550
issues for that reason.

00:15:49.550 --> 00:15:51.050
How could somebody
attack our system

00:15:51.050 --> 00:15:52.100
in such a way that [INAUDIBLE].

00:15:52.100 --> 00:15:52.860
I'm not an expert.

00:15:52.860 --> 00:15:55.520
I'm not some super infosec dude.

00:15:55.520 --> 00:15:59.700
But I tend to be better
at that than some people.

00:15:59.700 --> 00:16:02.060
I also, probably because
of some of the stuff

00:16:02.060 --> 00:16:06.850
that I've dealt with in my life,
and I think a lot about how

00:16:06.850 --> 00:16:12.056
things affect people, I
tend to empathize strongly

00:16:12.056 --> 00:16:12.680
with the users.

00:16:12.680 --> 00:16:15.222
And I think a lot about,
if we store data like this,

00:16:15.222 --> 00:16:17.180
how does that impact the
way that the user is--

00:16:17.180 --> 00:16:19.040
what they're able to do?

00:16:19.040 --> 00:16:22.430
And ultimately as a developer,
that's sort of my job

00:16:22.430 --> 00:16:23.540
is to make tools--

00:16:23.540 --> 00:16:27.730
not sort of, it is my job is
to make tools that people use.

00:16:27.730 --> 00:16:30.930
So it's rather helpful to be
able to empathize strongly

00:16:30.930 --> 00:16:32.590
with users or people.

00:16:32.590 --> 00:16:34.415
And it's often tough
because the people

00:16:34.415 --> 00:16:35.790
who are building
this stuff often

00:16:35.790 --> 00:16:37.373
have a lot of
difficulty understanding

00:16:37.373 --> 00:16:39.542
what it's like to be a user
of the thing they make.

00:16:39.542 --> 00:16:41.500
I'm a little bit better
at it than some people.

00:16:41.500 --> 00:16:43.290
Not perfect, but I'm
a little bit better

00:16:43.290 --> 00:16:45.530
than your average developer.

00:16:45.530 --> 00:16:49.030
Sometimes it absolutely
gives me superpowers.

00:16:49.030 --> 00:16:52.900
And sometimes it
absolutely ruins me.

00:16:52.900 --> 00:16:54.310
Sometimes when
something happens,

00:16:54.310 --> 00:16:56.990
when those emotions kick in
and I can't control them,

00:16:56.990 --> 00:16:58.870
it craters my day completely.

00:16:58.870 --> 00:17:01.250
It renders me unproductive.

00:17:01.250 --> 00:17:04.430
I can not do my
work effectively.

00:17:04.430 --> 00:17:07.369
I may not be able to
do my work period.

00:17:07.369 --> 00:17:08.750
I just can't.

00:17:08.750 --> 00:17:10.310
I cannot because I cannot focus.

00:17:10.310 --> 00:17:11.510
I cannot concentrate.

00:17:11.510 --> 00:17:12.440
I cannot do it.

00:17:18.920 --> 00:17:21.859
The toughest thing with all
of this in my life and dealing

00:17:21.859 --> 00:17:23.344
with this stuff where--

00:17:23.344 --> 00:17:25.760
you know, I've been dealing
with stuff, particularly ADHD.

00:17:25.760 --> 00:17:28.190
I've had that since
I was in school.

00:17:28.190 --> 00:17:29.340
I know the whole thing.

00:17:29.340 --> 00:17:31.430
I can think of things that I
did in second or third grade.

00:17:31.430 --> 00:17:33.140
I was like, oh, that
was what was going on.

00:17:33.140 --> 00:17:34.556
I wasn't diagnosed
until I was 27.

00:17:36.880 --> 00:17:39.350
But been dealing with
that the whole time.

00:17:39.350 --> 00:17:42.980
Anxiety and depression
started becoming much worse

00:17:42.980 --> 00:17:43.940
when I was 12 or 13.

00:17:46.432 --> 00:17:48.640
But in dealing with all
this, the toughest part of it

00:17:48.640 --> 00:17:52.840
for me was that feeling
alone, feeling like you

00:17:52.840 --> 00:17:55.240
were not like anyone
else around you,

00:17:55.240 --> 00:17:57.980
feeling as if
everybody else seems

00:17:57.980 --> 00:17:59.600
to be capable of
getting through life

00:17:59.600 --> 00:18:03.274
and seems to be OK with this
stuff and they seem to get--

00:18:03.274 --> 00:18:05.690
like in high school, they seem
to get their homework done.

00:18:05.690 --> 00:18:08.360
They can read 100 pages of
Dostoevsky in a night and be

00:18:08.360 --> 00:18:10.850
able to write something
about it, and I can't.

00:18:10.850 --> 00:18:12.050
What's the problem?

00:18:12.050 --> 00:18:13.460
Why can't I do this?

00:18:13.460 --> 00:18:15.500
And you feel, and I
felt for a long time

00:18:15.500 --> 00:18:20.290
that I was incapable
of living this life.

00:18:20.290 --> 00:18:22.120
I always screw up
and I always fail.

00:18:22.120 --> 00:18:24.860
And people that I love will
always grow tired of me

00:18:24.860 --> 00:18:25.360
and leave.

00:18:25.360 --> 00:18:27.670
And I will always do
that because I'm not

00:18:27.670 --> 00:18:30.220
capable of sustaining--

00:18:30.220 --> 00:18:31.660
doing things the right way.

00:18:31.660 --> 00:18:33.550
I always blow up and
something goes wrong.

00:18:33.550 --> 00:18:36.190
And that is how I felt for
a very, very long time.

00:18:43.180 --> 00:18:45.910
But there's a lot of
people who feel like that.

00:18:45.910 --> 00:18:48.400
A lot of people feel like that.

00:18:48.400 --> 00:18:53.970
And that is what I'm
here to talk about.

00:18:53.970 --> 00:18:59.150
And that is what we
formed OSMI to fight.

00:18:59.150 --> 00:19:01.870
To talk a little bit about
how this affects us--

00:19:01.870 --> 00:19:07.750
if we just look at the general
population, one in five adults

00:19:07.750 --> 00:19:10.180
have a mental disorder in
any one year in the US.

00:19:10.180 --> 00:19:12.910
That is 20% of the population.

00:19:12.910 --> 00:19:15.380
That is looking at the
general population.

00:19:15.380 --> 00:19:17.900
We'll get to the other
stuff in a minute.

00:19:17.900 --> 00:19:20.230
But at the very basic, if
we look general population,

00:19:20.230 --> 00:19:22.870
is it particularly abnormal
to have a mental disorder?

00:19:22.870 --> 00:19:25.110
No, it's actually not.

00:19:25.110 --> 00:19:29.120
In fact it's extremely common.

00:19:29.120 --> 00:19:31.100
Anxiety disorders
are the most common.

00:19:31.100 --> 00:19:34.496
They affect about 18%
of the population.

00:19:34.496 --> 00:19:37.120
The numbers add up to more than
20% because you typically have,

00:19:37.120 --> 00:19:38.350
again, co-morbidity.

00:19:38.350 --> 00:19:39.790
You have issues
where people will

00:19:39.790 --> 00:19:41.915
be diagnosed with multiple
things at the same time.

00:19:43.930 --> 00:19:45.530
There is a World
Health Organization

00:19:45.530 --> 00:19:48.740
study that was done in 2004 and
was released, I think, in 2008.

00:19:48.740 --> 00:19:51.230
And it's the most recent
study of what they call

00:19:51.230 --> 00:19:52.475
the global burden of disease.

00:19:55.500 --> 00:19:58.030
This idea of disease
burden is a metric

00:19:58.030 --> 00:20:00.940
they came up with which
combines premature death

00:20:00.940 --> 00:20:02.560
and years lived with disability.

00:20:02.560 --> 00:20:05.990
The idea is that they're
trying to measure

00:20:05.990 --> 00:20:08.570
the impact that a disease
has on a population.

00:20:11.390 --> 00:20:15.030
And in this study, they
found that the burden

00:20:15.030 --> 00:20:18.420
of mental disorders was
the largest of all disorder

00:20:18.420 --> 00:20:20.550
categories in North
America, larger

00:20:20.550 --> 00:20:25.100
than cardiovascular disease
and larger than cancer.

00:20:25.100 --> 00:20:27.860
And this is a quote
from this study.

00:20:27.860 --> 00:20:31.010
"In all regions,
neuropsychiatric conditions

00:20:31.010 --> 00:20:33.980
are the most important
causes of disability,

00:20:33.980 --> 00:20:36.860
accounting for
around 1/3 of years

00:20:36.860 --> 00:20:39.320
lost to disability among
adults aged 15 years over."

00:20:41.860 --> 00:20:44.580
The most important cause
of disability World Health

00:20:44.580 --> 00:20:46.810
Organization said.

00:20:46.810 --> 00:20:48.250
That is across the globe.

00:20:52.070 --> 00:20:53.060
Look at economic cost.

00:20:53.060 --> 00:20:55.185
And these things are always
kind of a little fuzzy,

00:20:55.185 --> 00:20:56.972
but it gives you some ideas.

00:20:56.972 --> 00:20:59.180
Mental health conditions
are the second leading cause

00:20:59.180 --> 00:21:02.820
of workplace absenteeism.

00:21:02.820 --> 00:21:06.180
I don't know what the first
is, but second, mental health

00:21:06.180 --> 00:21:08.160
conditions.

00:21:08.160 --> 00:21:11.720
If we're just looking
at depression,

00:21:11.720 --> 00:21:14.900
workers with depression
lose about 5.6 hours a week.

00:21:14.900 --> 00:21:18.170
Workers without lose about 1.5.

00:21:18.170 --> 00:21:21.604
That's a significant difference
in terms of hours lost.

00:21:21.604 --> 00:21:23.270
And if we look at
sort of these numbers,

00:21:23.270 --> 00:21:24.800
you try to attach
dollar figures to this.

00:21:24.800 --> 00:21:26.383
Again, it's always
a little bit fuzzy.

00:21:26.383 --> 00:21:28.550
But again, just
looking at depression,

00:21:28.550 --> 00:21:34.970
just one major category
of mental health disorder,

00:21:34.970 --> 00:21:39.840
$43.7 billion in absenteeism
from work, 200 million days

00:21:39.840 --> 00:21:40.340
lost.

00:21:40.340 --> 00:21:42.381
[INAUDIBLE] productivity,
direct treatment-- that

00:21:42.381 --> 00:21:45.380
is enormous impact, and
I think particularly

00:21:45.380 --> 00:21:49.370
if you think about people either
not working effectively or not

00:21:49.370 --> 00:21:52.850
being able to be in
the office at all.

00:21:52.850 --> 00:21:55.520
Because at the end of the
day, sick workers don't work.

00:21:55.520 --> 00:21:58.970
It doesn't matter what
they're sick with.

00:21:58.970 --> 00:22:02.650
People who are not healthy
are not as productive.

00:22:05.410 --> 00:22:07.620
Doesn't matter if
they have a cold.

00:22:07.620 --> 00:22:10.880
Doesn't matter if they got joint
pain and they can't get up,

00:22:10.880 --> 00:22:12.884
they've got a back problem.

00:22:12.884 --> 00:22:14.550
Doesn't matter if
they've got depression

00:22:14.550 --> 00:22:16.580
or they've got anxiety.

00:22:16.580 --> 00:22:18.504
It keeps them from
being as productive.

00:22:21.110 --> 00:22:23.546
Now we have, for
a couple of years,

00:22:23.546 --> 00:22:25.670
done what we call the mental
health in tech survey.

00:22:25.670 --> 00:22:28.490
And this is an opt-in
survey, so self-selective.

00:22:28.490 --> 00:22:30.680
So keep that in mind
if we go up and look

00:22:30.680 --> 00:22:32.030
at some of the deeper results.

00:22:32.030 --> 00:22:34.160
But these are results
from our 2016 initiative,

00:22:34.160 --> 00:22:35.660
which has so far--

00:22:35.660 --> 00:22:36.680
it's still open.

00:22:36.680 --> 00:22:38.900
If you want to take it,
that would be great.

00:22:38.900 --> 00:22:42.650
But this is data that
we had from 2016.

00:22:42.650 --> 00:22:45.680
As of November 16, this
is what it collected.

00:22:45.680 --> 00:22:47.720
And this just includes
people in the US,

00:22:47.720 --> 00:22:50.420
and it just includes
non self-employed folks.

00:22:50.420 --> 00:22:52.870
The reason I did that
was because there

00:22:52.870 --> 00:22:54.650
are some differences
about the US compared

00:22:54.650 --> 00:22:56.030
with other countries.

00:22:56.030 --> 00:22:58.490
Typically in the
US, your workplace

00:22:58.490 --> 00:23:01.390
is your primary conduit
for health care.

00:23:01.390 --> 00:23:04.120
And people who are self-employed
have a different situation.

00:23:04.120 --> 00:23:05.940
They are their own boss.

00:23:05.940 --> 00:23:07.690
They can say, I'm going
to take a day off.

00:23:07.690 --> 00:23:09.610
I'm going to go get
treatment for this.

00:23:09.610 --> 00:23:11.650
They have different
opportunities.

00:23:11.650 --> 00:23:15.310
People who are employed
by an organization

00:23:15.310 --> 00:23:17.017
have to work with
that organization

00:23:17.017 --> 00:23:17.850
and what they offer.

00:23:20.640 --> 00:23:23.250
So the four questions that
I want to show you-- there

00:23:23.250 --> 00:23:27.110
is tons of data in here from
all people all over the world.

00:23:27.110 --> 00:23:29.200
And we have about
1,500 responses.

00:23:29.200 --> 00:23:31.182
This is just the
folks in the US.

00:23:31.182 --> 00:23:33.390
First question, do you think
that discussing a health

00:23:33.390 --> 00:23:37.650
issue with your employer would
have negative consequences?

00:23:37.650 --> 00:23:40.290
We asked about physical health.

00:23:40.290 --> 00:23:43.620
72% of people said
no, about 3/4.

00:23:43.620 --> 00:23:45.540
Maybe said 25%.

00:23:45.540 --> 00:23:47.540
Yes said 4%.

00:23:47.540 --> 00:23:51.179
4% said yes, excuse me.

00:23:51.179 --> 00:23:53.470
Most people feel that if they
discuss a physical health

00:23:53.470 --> 00:23:55.660
issue, probably would not
be negative consequences

00:23:55.660 --> 00:23:57.280
in the tech workplace.

00:23:57.280 --> 00:24:02.500
For mental health, only
about a third said no.

00:24:02.500 --> 00:24:06.380
About 2/3 said yes or maybe.

00:24:06.380 --> 00:24:08.850
That's a very
significant difference,

00:24:08.850 --> 00:24:12.430
and I think underlines
the attitudes

00:24:12.430 --> 00:24:15.280
and perception of mental
health and the consequences

00:24:15.280 --> 00:24:19.980
for speaking about it
openly in the workplace.

00:24:19.980 --> 00:24:21.560
Would you bring
up a health issue

00:24:21.560 --> 00:24:23.600
with a potential
employer in an interview?

00:24:23.600 --> 00:24:26.650
And again, we split this
between physical and mental.

00:24:26.650 --> 00:24:31.220
With physical, no
and maybe, 76%.

00:24:31.220 --> 00:24:32.180
It's not surprising.

00:24:32.180 --> 00:24:33.721
Most people don't
want to give people

00:24:33.721 --> 00:24:36.902
a reason not to hire them.

00:24:36.902 --> 00:24:39.110
There are a number of issues
that could go into that.

00:24:39.110 --> 00:24:40.568
Some would be like,
well, what does

00:24:40.568 --> 00:24:43.010
it matter if my knee acts
up every once in a while?

00:24:43.010 --> 00:24:45.052
Some people will tell you
there is no way in heck

00:24:45.052 --> 00:24:46.760
you should ever tell
somebody that you're

00:24:46.760 --> 00:24:49.100
planning on getting pregnant
because you will not

00:24:49.100 --> 00:24:50.730
get the job.

00:24:50.730 --> 00:24:52.800
That is a physical health issue.

00:24:52.800 --> 00:24:54.775
So again, there's
lots of reasons.

00:24:57.790 --> 00:25:00.690
But yes, 24%, not that high.

00:25:00.690 --> 00:25:03.320
Let's compare that
with mental health.

00:25:03.320 --> 00:25:06.290
Only 7% of people said yes.

00:25:06.290 --> 00:25:08.480
Twice as many said no.

00:25:08.480 --> 00:25:10.520
Maybe was a little bit
lower, probably being

00:25:10.520 --> 00:25:13.156
eaten up by that no.

00:25:13.156 --> 00:25:15.280
This in fact is higher than
the numbers-- or excuse

00:25:15.280 --> 00:25:17.613
me, this is in fact a little
bit better than the numbers

00:25:17.613 --> 00:25:20.630
we had in 2014 when we
last did this survey.

00:25:20.630 --> 00:25:25.964
But it is still the case that
far fewer people would bring up

00:25:25.964 --> 00:25:27.880
a mental health issue
versus a physical health

00:25:27.880 --> 00:25:30.671
issue in an interview
because they believe--

00:25:30.671 --> 00:25:32.170
I believe what you
can get from that

00:25:32.170 --> 00:25:34.510
is they believe it is more
likely that a mental health

00:25:34.510 --> 00:25:39.720
issue will be something that
eliminates them from contention

00:25:39.720 --> 00:25:40.532
for that job.

00:25:40.532 --> 00:25:42.490
Now this is despite the
fact that the Americans

00:25:42.490 --> 00:25:44.820
With Disability Act says it
is illegal to do so if you

00:25:44.820 --> 00:25:46.977
have more than 15 employees.

00:25:46.977 --> 00:25:48.810
But it's also almost
impossible to prove it.

00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:55.294
Does your employer
provide resources

00:25:55.294 --> 00:25:56.960
to learn more about
mental health issues

00:25:56.960 --> 00:25:59.705
and how to seek help?

00:25:59.705 --> 00:26:02.080
Again, the workplace being
the primary conduit for health

00:26:02.080 --> 00:26:04.620
care, how does the
workplace educate?

00:26:04.620 --> 00:26:06.620
How does the workplace
point out these resources

00:26:06.620 --> 00:26:09.580
and their availability
and things like that?

00:26:09.580 --> 00:26:12.221
Only 30% said yes.

00:26:12.221 --> 00:26:17.739
So 70% say no, employer
does not provide resources.

00:26:17.739 --> 00:26:19.280
And another third
says, I don't know,

00:26:19.280 --> 00:26:20.910
which I think is
just as bad as no.

00:26:26.300 --> 00:26:30.672
2/3 of folks who are working
as tech professionals,

00:26:30.672 --> 00:26:32.130
their employer
isn't providing them

00:26:32.130 --> 00:26:34.032
with resources
about mental health.

00:26:34.032 --> 00:26:35.990
Keep in mind what the
World Health Organization

00:26:35.990 --> 00:26:37.990
said about the importance
of this and the burden

00:26:37.990 --> 00:26:41.475
that it has on our society.

00:26:41.475 --> 00:26:43.850
And the fourth and last question
that I'll show you here,

00:26:43.850 --> 00:26:45.332
do you feel that
being identified

00:26:45.332 --> 00:26:47.915
as a person with a mental health
issue would hurt your career?

00:26:53.900 --> 00:27:00.570
And those numbers, only 12%
said no, I don't think it would,

00:27:00.570 --> 00:27:04.330
or no it has not.

00:27:04.330 --> 00:27:10.370
Everyone else says maybe or yes
I think it would or yes it has.

00:27:10.370 --> 00:27:14.240
The perception is such
that people believe,

00:27:14.240 --> 00:27:16.980
87% of folks who
answer these questions,

00:27:16.980 --> 00:27:19.580
believe that being identified
as somebody with a mental health

00:27:19.580 --> 00:27:22.200
issue is going to
hurt their career.

00:27:22.200 --> 00:27:24.056
Why would they be
willing to discuss it?

00:27:24.056 --> 00:27:25.680
Why would they be
willing to seek help?

00:27:25.680 --> 00:27:28.550
Why would they be
willing to get better,

00:27:28.550 --> 00:27:30.939
as that workplace is a
conduit for health care,

00:27:30.939 --> 00:27:33.230
if they think there's going
to be negative consequences

00:27:33.230 --> 00:27:38.190
for being known as that/ I
think that's a great question.

00:27:38.190 --> 00:27:41.630
I think a lot of people are
very afraid to discuss it.

00:27:41.630 --> 00:27:44.660
And it's tough because
change is really hard,

00:27:44.660 --> 00:27:47.280
because we are scared.

00:27:47.280 --> 00:27:49.563
Because frequently the
things I've encountered

00:27:49.563 --> 00:27:53.330
is that people just
don't know what to do.

00:27:53.330 --> 00:27:55.700
Employers are people
working in the workplace who

00:27:55.700 --> 00:27:57.590
have some responsibility
for this stuff.

00:27:57.590 --> 00:28:00.140
They're often afraid of
endangering their workplace,

00:28:00.140 --> 00:28:06.050
saying the wrong thing,
giving the wrong advice,

00:28:06.050 --> 00:28:10.380
and endangering their
workplace as a result--

00:28:10.380 --> 00:28:14.160
endangering the health of the
organization, the existence

00:28:14.160 --> 00:28:16.080
of the organization.

00:28:16.080 --> 00:28:17.580
And people who are
employed are also

00:28:17.580 --> 00:28:21.306
afraid of losing their
jobs, as is demonstrated

00:28:21.306 --> 00:28:22.430
in the information we have.

00:28:22.430 --> 00:28:24.170
People are afraid
to lose their jobs

00:28:24.170 --> 00:28:28.650
because they're afraid that
they'll be identified as that.

00:28:28.650 --> 00:28:31.950
Now at OSMI, there are
things we can do to help.

00:28:31.950 --> 00:28:33.700
There's a lot of things
we can do to help.

00:28:33.700 --> 00:28:36.033
But there's five things that
I think you can think about

00:28:36.033 --> 00:28:38.370
right now that I think
will be effective

00:28:38.370 --> 00:28:39.702
and I think will help.

00:28:39.702 --> 00:28:41.910
The first thing is-- and
this is kind of a meta thing

00:28:41.910 --> 00:28:44.118
and it's kind of hard, you
know, what does this mean?

00:28:44.118 --> 00:28:47.004
Make a commitment to change.

00:28:47.004 --> 00:28:48.420
But I think
fundamentally you have

00:28:48.420 --> 00:28:54.410
to make a decision that you're
going to think and speak

00:28:54.410 --> 00:29:01.062
about mental health differently
than you do right now.

00:29:01.062 --> 00:29:03.360
And that's a matter
of changing yourself.

00:29:03.360 --> 00:29:05.860
And it doesn't mean that you
have to go around and say, hey,

00:29:05.860 --> 00:29:06.990
I've got this thing.

00:29:06.990 --> 00:29:10.571
You know what, my brother,
he did this, my sister.

00:29:10.571 --> 00:29:11.820
You do not have to be like me.

00:29:11.820 --> 00:29:14.160
My therapist says I have a
confessional personality,

00:29:14.160 --> 00:29:17.340
and that is very accurate.

00:29:17.340 --> 00:29:20.800
I am a bit of an
oversharer, let's say.

00:29:20.800 --> 00:29:22.540
And that works out
for stuff like this.

00:29:22.540 --> 00:29:24.470
I'm good at this
because I can do that.

00:29:24.470 --> 00:29:26.178
It doesn't mean you
have to be like this.

00:29:26.178 --> 00:29:30.160
But being able to speak openly
about mental health issues

00:29:30.160 --> 00:29:33.220
and speak to it without shame
and emphasize that there's

00:29:33.220 --> 00:29:38.270
no shame in it, that
can change that world

00:29:38.270 --> 00:29:41.220
around you, the social group
that interacts with you.

00:29:44.179 --> 00:29:45.970
The social group you
interact with the most

00:29:45.970 --> 00:29:49.600
is probably your workplace,
for better or for worse.

00:29:49.600 --> 00:29:53.430
Those are probably people
you spend the most time with.

00:29:53.430 --> 00:29:57.060
And you can have a significant
impact on those people

00:29:57.060 --> 00:30:00.060
if you indicate to
them that they can

00:30:00.060 --> 00:30:03.510
be less afraid of this stuff.

00:30:03.510 --> 00:30:06.300
It is almost certain
based on the numbers

00:30:06.300 --> 00:30:08.070
that there are people
in your social group

00:30:08.070 --> 00:30:10.230
who are dealing with
mental health issues

00:30:10.230 --> 00:30:13.620
and are afraid to
talk about, right now,

00:30:13.620 --> 00:30:14.960
and you don't know who they are.

00:30:18.160 --> 00:30:20.170
If you're able to speak
more openly about it,

00:30:20.170 --> 00:30:23.690
you will help those people
feel safer, feel less stressed,

00:30:23.690 --> 00:30:27.320
be mentally healthier, and be
more likely to seek treatment.

00:30:30.220 --> 00:30:32.470
The second thing you can do
is we've created handbooks

00:30:32.470 --> 00:30:35.680
specifically to help people
with these kinds of issues.

00:30:35.680 --> 00:30:36.580
We have three.

00:30:36.580 --> 00:30:39.690
They are available
for free as e-books.

00:30:42.410 --> 00:30:45.460
There are handbooks for
employers and employees

00:30:45.460 --> 00:30:48.700
on how to navigate ADA law
specifically dedicated to tech

00:30:48.700 --> 00:30:50.342
workplaces and mental health.

00:30:50.342 --> 00:30:51.550
So there's one for employers.

00:30:51.550 --> 00:30:54.700
There's one for employees
dealing with ADA law.

00:30:54.700 --> 00:30:58.570
The third one is how to create
supportive workplaces that

00:30:58.570 --> 00:31:03.400
promote mental wellness
within the workplace.

00:31:03.400 --> 00:31:04.960
All three of these
were developed

00:31:04.960 --> 00:31:07.660
by Jennifer Akullian--

00:31:07.660 --> 00:31:09.950
who has a PhD in psychology.

00:31:09.950 --> 00:31:12.520
She works at Keen IO--

00:31:12.520 --> 00:31:14.440
with a little bit
of help from me

00:31:14.440 --> 00:31:16.490
and some help from
Johanne Wu, who

00:31:16.490 --> 00:31:21.036
is a PhD in
organizational psychology.

00:31:21.036 --> 00:31:22.660
These handbooks are
available for free.

00:31:22.660 --> 00:31:24.940
They're Creative
Commons licensed.

00:31:24.940 --> 00:31:28.440
And you can get them
right now at our website.

00:31:28.440 --> 00:31:31.129
The third thing you
can do is take a course

00:31:31.129 --> 00:31:32.420
called mental health first aid.

00:31:32.420 --> 00:31:33.680
It's an eight hour course.

00:31:33.680 --> 00:31:35.180
You can find lots
and lots of people

00:31:35.180 --> 00:31:37.650
who will teach it in
this area, or in almost

00:31:37.650 --> 00:31:38.900
any other part of the country.

00:31:38.900 --> 00:31:41.120
It is available in 22
different countries.

00:31:41.120 --> 00:31:45.056
In the US, I paid $50 to take
it and I got lunch with it.

00:31:45.056 --> 00:31:46.430
It was a nice
little boxed lunch.

00:31:46.430 --> 00:31:47.960
It was really pleasant.

00:31:47.960 --> 00:31:49.850
And that was really cool.

00:31:49.850 --> 00:31:54.680
And I learned a ton
about how to identify

00:31:54.680 --> 00:31:57.130
if someone is in a
mental health crisis,

00:31:57.130 --> 00:32:03.280
and then how to interact
with them most effectively

00:32:03.280 --> 00:32:06.460
so that they are more
likely to seek help.

00:32:06.460 --> 00:32:07.900
The key here is--
you might notice

00:32:07.900 --> 00:32:11.230
I did not say how to fix
their problem for them.

00:32:11.230 --> 00:32:12.130
That is not your job.

00:32:12.130 --> 00:32:13.030
You are not trained for that.

00:32:13.030 --> 00:32:14.320
I'm not trained for that.

00:32:14.320 --> 00:32:15.774
Do not try to fix their problem.

00:32:15.774 --> 00:32:17.440
People in tech,
particularly developers,

00:32:17.440 --> 00:32:19.960
want to solve
problems for people.

00:32:19.960 --> 00:32:20.995
Do not do this.

00:32:20.995 --> 00:32:23.360
This is not your job.

00:32:23.360 --> 00:32:25.710
You don't have to
fix everything.

00:32:25.710 --> 00:32:28.390
You listen empathetically
and talk to them

00:32:28.390 --> 00:32:30.700
in a way that's going to
encourage them to seek help.

00:32:30.700 --> 00:32:32.470
I think it's a very
important course to take.

00:32:32.470 --> 00:32:34.178
I particularly think
if you have anything

00:32:34.178 --> 00:32:37.930
to do with managing people, this
is an essential course to take,

00:32:37.930 --> 00:32:40.150
because you will
learn a lot about how

00:32:40.150 --> 00:32:44.170
to interact with people in a
rewarding and positive way that

00:32:44.170 --> 00:32:47.116
helps them succeed.

00:32:47.116 --> 00:32:48.990
Tell people about the
work that you're doing,

00:32:48.990 --> 00:32:49.820
the efforts that you're doing.

00:32:49.820 --> 00:32:51.070
You take this class.

00:32:51.070 --> 00:32:52.530
You read these handbooks.

00:32:52.530 --> 00:32:53.587
Talk about it openly.

00:32:53.587 --> 00:32:54.420
Share it on Twitter.

00:32:54.420 --> 00:32:55.294
Share it on Facebook.

00:32:55.294 --> 00:32:58.650
Share it on Google+.

00:32:58.650 --> 00:33:01.150
Take a selfie when you're on
a break at the training course

00:33:01.150 --> 00:33:02.566
and say hey, I'm
doing this thing.

00:33:02.566 --> 00:33:03.910
It's really super cool.

00:33:03.910 --> 00:33:05.289
Talk about it.

00:33:05.289 --> 00:33:07.330
The more you talk about
it, the people around you

00:33:07.330 --> 00:33:10.030
will be less afraid.

00:33:10.030 --> 00:33:12.096
I guarantee it.

00:33:12.096 --> 00:33:15.520
And the fifth thing, and I
think the most important thing,

00:33:15.520 --> 00:33:16.890
this is about peer support.

00:33:16.890 --> 00:33:18.450
And there's certain
organizations

00:33:18.450 --> 00:33:20.485
like "Nami," NAMI--

00:33:20.485 --> 00:33:22.110
can't write exactly
what it stands for,

00:33:22.110 --> 00:33:23.875
National Association
of the Mentally Ill.

00:33:23.875 --> 00:33:25.770
I probably got wrong.

00:33:25.770 --> 00:33:28.960
Really focus on peer support.

00:33:28.960 --> 00:33:31.940
Tell people that they
matter in your life,

00:33:31.940 --> 00:33:33.670
how they impact
your life positively

00:33:33.670 --> 00:33:36.400
and how strong and
great they are.

00:33:36.400 --> 00:33:38.380
Everybody needs to hear this.

00:33:38.380 --> 00:33:41.200
There are few of us who would
not benefit from hearing this

00:33:41.200 --> 00:33:43.000
from the external sources.

00:33:43.000 --> 00:33:44.830
There are few of us
who have a voice so

00:33:44.830 --> 00:33:46.930
strong within
themselves that they

00:33:46.930 --> 00:33:50.020
don't need it from anyone else.

00:33:50.020 --> 00:33:52.870
Everybody needs to hear
this, particularly people

00:33:52.870 --> 00:33:54.992
whose brains lie to them.

00:33:54.992 --> 00:33:59.970
And my brain has been lying
to me for most of my life,

00:33:59.970 --> 00:34:02.130
telling me that I didn't
matter, that all I

00:34:02.130 --> 00:34:04.770
did was screw things up and
I was a burden to people.

00:34:07.231 --> 00:34:08.480
So what's the upside for this?

00:34:08.480 --> 00:34:11.139
And I don't talk about
just the upside for--

00:34:11.139 --> 00:34:12.139
people, you feel better.

00:34:12.139 --> 00:34:14.659
You feel that you've
done some moral good.

00:34:14.659 --> 00:34:16.139
Why try to change the workplace?

00:34:16.139 --> 00:34:17.750
What's the upside
for the workplace?

00:34:17.750 --> 00:34:18.260
And why?

00:34:18.260 --> 00:34:20.330
Because it benefits the
organization and everyone

00:34:20.330 --> 00:34:21.050
in it.

00:34:21.050 --> 00:34:24.500
Because mental wellness means
better employees, period.

00:34:24.500 --> 00:34:29.420
Employees feel valued and secure
and work more effectively when

00:34:29.420 --> 00:34:33.354
employers demonstrate
commitment to their well-being.

00:34:33.354 --> 00:34:37.030
And people are going to
want to work for you.

00:34:37.030 --> 00:34:39.699
People want to work someplace
that respects them fully

00:34:39.699 --> 00:34:41.408
and that doesn't ignore
their well-being.

00:34:41.408 --> 00:34:43.032
If I go back and I
think about the jobs

00:34:43.032 --> 00:34:44.710
that I liked in my
career and the jobs

00:34:44.710 --> 00:34:47.050
that I haven't liked,
the ones that are liked,

00:34:47.050 --> 00:34:49.630
it did not have a lot to do
with the work I was doing.

00:34:49.630 --> 00:34:51.770
It had to do with the people.

00:34:51.770 --> 00:34:53.770
Did I have good relationships
with those people,

00:34:53.770 --> 00:34:56.370
respectful relationships?

00:34:56.370 --> 00:35:01.080
Did we have a mutual respect
and concern for each other?

00:35:01.080 --> 00:35:02.850
The people that I
always work hardest for

00:35:02.850 --> 00:35:07.080
were people that I felt like had
concern about me as a person.

00:35:07.080 --> 00:35:09.450
They were concerned
about my well-being.

00:35:09.450 --> 00:35:13.310
They wanted me to be
happy and healthy.

00:35:13.310 --> 00:35:17.395
That's what makes for a good
workplace, not ping pong tables

00:35:17.395 --> 00:35:19.480
and not free lunches.

00:35:19.480 --> 00:35:21.105
That's what makes
for a good workplace.

00:35:23.780 --> 00:35:28.710
In 2016, Open Sourcing Mental
Illness was not a nonprofit.

00:35:28.710 --> 00:35:31.680
It was just a dude,
me, who had some ideas.

00:35:31.680 --> 00:35:34.895
That's all it was.

00:35:34.895 --> 00:35:37.257
I started to make
some changes though

00:35:37.257 --> 00:35:39.590
to do some stuff that was
maybe a little more ambitious.

00:35:39.590 --> 00:35:42.131
I had been speaking about mental
health for about three years

00:35:42.131 --> 00:35:43.440
at different tech conferences.

00:35:43.440 --> 00:35:44.427
It was mostly just me.

00:35:44.427 --> 00:35:45.260
It's mostly just me.

00:35:45.260 --> 00:35:47.510
We had started a little bit
of work on those handbooks

00:35:47.510 --> 00:35:48.200
I talked about.

00:35:48.200 --> 00:35:49.100
That was about it.

00:35:49.100 --> 00:35:52.414
But in 2016 we had
some goals, and we

00:35:52.414 --> 00:35:54.080
tried to get some
money for those goals.

00:35:54.080 --> 00:35:56.760
Those goals primarily were
to become a legal nonprofit,

00:35:56.760 --> 00:36:00.332
501(c)(3) to create e-books
and printed handbooks--

00:36:00.332 --> 00:36:02.790
the handbooks we put together
were not e-books at the time.

00:36:02.790 --> 00:36:04.290
You couldn't put
them on your Kindle

00:36:04.290 --> 00:36:06.090
and fly around with
them, stuff like that--

00:36:06.090 --> 00:36:10.730
to release an API and release
our survey data from 2016--

00:36:10.730 --> 00:36:12.740
to do another survey too--

00:36:12.740 --> 00:36:16.370
to do a video presentation
series, to do a video workshop,

00:36:16.370 --> 00:36:19.160
and to get more people talking
and speaking about this.

00:36:19.160 --> 00:36:20.700
So I wanted to raise some money.

00:36:20.700 --> 00:36:21.900
I did this on Indiegogo.

00:36:21.900 --> 00:36:23.990
Again, this was really people
were just giving me money.

00:36:23.990 --> 00:36:25.490
There was no
organization behind it.

