00:45:13.995 --> 00:45:17.384
And so the question
here Ed is, I've

00:45:17.384 --> 00:45:19.800
been suffering from an episode
of major depression for two

00:45:19.800 --> 00:45:20.760
years.

00:45:20.760 --> 00:45:22.260
Do you have advice
for how to combat

00:45:22.260 --> 00:45:23.610
negative thoughts at work?

00:45:23.610 --> 00:45:26.550
It's often hard for me to see
the positive side of project

00:45:26.550 --> 00:45:29.010
proposals and designs even
when it feels like others can.

00:45:31.590 --> 00:45:36.650
ED FINKLER: I smirk because
that sounds familiar to me.

00:45:40.360 --> 00:45:43.480
Advice is tough
because something

00:45:43.480 --> 00:45:45.644
that I've learned
sometimes the hard way

00:45:45.644 --> 00:45:47.560
is that you shouldn't
give advice about things

00:45:47.560 --> 00:45:52.401
that you don't actually have
enough expertise to speak on.

00:45:52.401 --> 00:45:54.400
And one of the things
that also I think you find

00:45:54.400 --> 00:45:56.566
is that particularly when
dealing with mental health

00:45:56.566 --> 00:46:00.130
issues, things that work
for one person often

00:46:00.130 --> 00:46:03.580
don't matter at all.

00:46:03.580 --> 00:46:06.580
I feel better when I
drink a lot of water.

00:46:06.580 --> 00:46:07.394
I do.

00:46:07.394 --> 00:46:09.560
Doesn't mean you're going
to feel better because you

00:46:09.560 --> 00:46:10.393
drink lots of water.

00:46:10.393 --> 00:46:11.940
Maybe it's a good idea.

00:46:11.940 --> 00:46:13.730
Hey, hydrate, that's awesome.

00:46:13.730 --> 00:46:17.780
That doesn't mean that's
going to fix your problems.

00:46:17.780 --> 00:46:23.599
So advice is tough
because there's not an,

00:46:23.599 --> 00:46:25.640
oh, that's the way you
solve that kind of problem

00:46:25.640 --> 00:46:26.840
situation for everybody.

00:46:26.840 --> 00:46:29.900
I think the thing
that I would suggest

00:46:29.900 --> 00:46:34.560
is that the person who's
dealing with this, first off,

00:46:34.560 --> 00:46:37.200
that sounds really tough.

00:46:37.200 --> 00:46:39.750
And that must be very
hard, particularly

00:46:39.750 --> 00:46:42.540
to feel like everybody
else seems like they're

00:46:42.540 --> 00:46:44.910
dealing with it OK and I'm not.

00:46:47.420 --> 00:46:48.830
I know that's not fun.

00:46:48.830 --> 00:46:51.050
I'm not going to say I
understand every single thing

00:46:51.050 --> 00:46:52.008
everybody goes through.

00:46:52.008 --> 00:46:52.970
I don't.

00:46:52.970 --> 00:46:57.050
But that's something I
know a little bit about.

00:46:57.050 --> 00:47:01.460
So I can't give you
specific advice.

00:47:01.460 --> 00:47:08.120
But what I can say is
that taking that step

00:47:08.120 --> 00:47:15.661
to speak to somebody about
it, an particularly somebody

00:47:15.661 --> 00:47:17.410
who's a mental health
professional I think

00:47:17.410 --> 00:47:18.950
is really important.

00:47:18.950 --> 00:47:21.440
That can be really
scary though too.

00:47:21.440 --> 00:47:24.890
Oftentimes you're overcoming
a huge amount of inertia

00:47:24.890 --> 00:47:27.595
to not do anything.

00:47:27.595 --> 00:47:28.970
I've run into
people who have had

00:47:28.970 --> 00:47:31.370
maybe occasionally bad
experiences with one therapist

00:47:31.370 --> 00:47:33.590
and they're like, I don't ever
want to see somebody again,

00:47:33.590 --> 00:47:34.173
it's terrible.

00:47:34.173 --> 00:47:36.380
Or there's a lot of
stuff hung up on that.

00:47:36.380 --> 00:47:39.480
And it could be many reasons.

00:47:39.480 --> 00:47:44.550
The first thing I
hope is that they

00:47:44.550 --> 00:47:50.010
have a peer around them who they
can speak with openly about.

00:47:50.010 --> 00:47:52.200
And I hope everybody
thinks about

00:47:52.200 --> 00:47:54.060
that as maybe you're that peer.

00:47:56.780 --> 00:47:58.150
It's one of your co-employees.

00:47:58.150 --> 00:48:00.030
It could be anybody
who's saying this.

00:48:00.030 --> 00:48:01.530
And this is not
an uncommon thing.

00:48:06.610 --> 00:48:12.520
People in this situation are
afraid, typically, very afraid.

00:48:12.520 --> 00:48:16.300
And even if you don't deal
with this stuff yourself,

00:48:16.300 --> 00:48:19.030
you can have an
immense positive impact

00:48:19.030 --> 00:48:22.810
on someone's life by simply
helping them not feel

00:48:22.810 --> 00:48:26.220
like they have to be afraid.

00:48:26.220 --> 00:48:29.180
And it doesn't mean fixing
their problem for them.

00:48:29.180 --> 00:48:32.820
But what it means is that
you're not going to judge them.

00:48:32.820 --> 00:48:35.370
You're not going to view
it as a character flaw.

00:48:35.370 --> 00:48:41.240
You're going to listen
empathetically and be

00:48:41.240 --> 00:48:42.680
encouraging towards them.

00:48:42.680 --> 00:48:45.080
Say hey, it's OK.

00:48:45.080 --> 00:48:46.770
We're going to figure this out.

00:48:46.770 --> 00:48:48.770
The thing that I would
probably do in this case,

00:48:48.770 --> 00:48:50.660
from a practical
standpoint, it sounds

00:48:50.660 --> 00:48:53.170
like there's good
resources here at Google,

00:48:53.170 --> 00:48:55.580
in your EAP and other things.

00:48:55.580 --> 00:48:57.590
I would look at what
those resources are.

00:48:57.590 --> 00:48:59.690
I would identify
somebody who specifically

00:48:59.690 --> 00:49:02.350
deals with depression.

00:49:02.350 --> 00:49:05.600
And I'd go try to speak with
a professional about that.

00:49:05.600 --> 00:49:08.680
That can be scary.

00:49:08.680 --> 00:49:12.570
But it is harder and
it's probably not

00:49:12.570 --> 00:49:16.700
going to get better until
you start seeking treatment.

00:49:16.700 --> 00:49:21.200
And I guess I'd ask
everybody around here, again,

00:49:21.200 --> 00:49:24.050
if we're speaking
openly and honestly

00:49:24.050 --> 00:49:26.780
and positively about
mental health, that

00:49:26.780 --> 00:49:29.570
is something that's going
to help people like this

00:49:29.570 --> 00:49:31.760
be more willing to get
the help that they need

00:49:31.760 --> 00:49:33.080
and not have to suffer.

00:49:33.080 --> 00:49:34.880
This is exactly what
I'm talking about when

00:49:34.880 --> 00:49:36.200
I say people suffer in silence.

00:49:39.130 --> 00:49:44.360
And so practically speaking,
you want to get help.

00:49:44.360 --> 00:49:46.370
If you need somebody,
find someone hopefully

00:49:46.370 --> 00:49:48.364
that you can trust
who maybe you can

00:49:48.364 --> 00:49:50.030
talk about this a
little bit with if you

00:49:50.030 --> 00:49:52.310
need some help
getting to that point

00:49:52.310 --> 00:49:54.507
where you can seek out help.

00:49:54.507 --> 00:49:56.090
And maybe they can
help you with that.

00:49:56.090 --> 00:49:58.820
Be a person, folks
here, be a person

00:49:58.820 --> 00:50:02.150
who somebody could turn to and
say, I'm scared to do this.

00:50:02.150 --> 00:50:03.080
Can you help me?

00:50:03.080 --> 00:50:05.510
Could you maybe help me
set up the appointment?

00:50:05.510 --> 00:50:10.700
Could you maybe go with
me and just sit outside.

00:50:10.700 --> 00:50:14.660
I constantly run into folks
who are afraid to go seek help.

00:50:14.660 --> 00:50:19.704
And just being that person
for them and saying,

00:50:19.704 --> 00:50:20.870
yeah, I'm going to help you.

00:50:20.870 --> 00:50:24.380
If you need, I will call
to set that appointment up.

00:50:24.380 --> 00:50:29.260
But I'm here for you,
whatever you need.

00:50:29.260 --> 00:50:33.610
Being that person is what
this person needs the most.

00:50:33.610 --> 00:50:36.430
And it's going to be a lot
easier for them, I think,

00:50:36.430 --> 00:50:38.240
if we can all do that.

00:50:38.240 --> 00:50:43.480
So that's why I'd say, look at
what you've got in your EAP.

00:50:43.480 --> 00:50:44.920
The woman who
spoke earlier I bet

00:50:44.920 --> 00:50:47.440
would have some specific
stuff you could help with.

00:50:47.440 --> 00:50:48.940
Just go and talk
and say-- you don't

00:50:48.940 --> 00:50:50.080
have to spill your whole guts.

00:50:50.080 --> 00:50:51.996
Just say, hey, I've been
having some problems.

00:50:51.996 --> 00:50:53.620
I think it's related
to depression.

00:50:53.620 --> 00:50:57.790
I would like to speak
privately with somebody.

00:50:57.790 --> 00:50:59.690
That's all you've got to do.

00:50:59.690 --> 00:51:02.580
And that's the first
step to getting better.

00:51:02.580 --> 00:51:03.680
And there is treatment.

00:51:03.680 --> 00:51:05.480
There are things
available for you.

00:51:05.480 --> 00:51:07.899
This can and will get better.

00:51:07.899 --> 00:51:09.440
Just got to go seek
the help and find

00:51:09.440 --> 00:51:11.505
the people who can
help you with it.

00:51:11.505 --> 00:51:14.079
So yeah, that's what I'd say.

00:51:14.079 --> 00:51:16.620
SPEAKER: And being mindful of
the time, if you have questions

00:51:16.620 --> 00:51:19.800
for Ed, you can always
approach him after the talk,

00:51:19.800 --> 00:51:21.580
as he mentioned a
little bit earlier.

00:51:21.580 --> 00:51:23.520
I do have one question
of my own as well.

00:51:23.520 --> 00:51:27.180
Just in your experience
speaking on the lecture circuit

00:51:27.180 --> 00:51:29.230
and also just working
with companies,

00:51:29.230 --> 00:51:32.100
are there any success
stories or any use cases

00:51:32.100 --> 00:51:34.280
that you've seen
examples from folks

00:51:34.280 --> 00:51:36.730
you've spoken with at companies?

00:51:36.730 --> 00:51:43.090
ED FINKLER: Yeah, the
first thing I'd say

00:51:43.090 --> 00:51:45.970
is that I can speak
to this directly

00:51:45.970 --> 00:51:51.400
in that when I go up and
speak about this stuff,

00:51:51.400 --> 00:51:53.620
every time I speak I
have people come up to me

00:51:53.620 --> 00:51:57.490
and say how important it was
for them to just hear somebody

00:51:57.490 --> 00:52:01.360
speak openly without
fear about mental health,

00:52:01.360 --> 00:52:06.729
that just that act can be
transformative for them.

00:52:06.729 --> 00:52:08.520
And that is humbling
because that is weird.

00:52:08.520 --> 00:52:11.100
I'm just up here
babbling about stuff.

00:52:11.100 --> 00:52:14.680
I'm oversharing and
acting like I'm an expert.

00:52:14.680 --> 00:52:15.680
I don't know if I am.

00:52:15.680 --> 00:52:17.850
I don't know.

00:52:17.850 --> 00:52:21.290
But just that, I
guess, if you're

00:52:21.290 --> 00:52:23.120
talking about success
stories, I see

00:52:23.120 --> 00:52:25.650
that as a big success story,
because every time I talk

00:52:25.650 --> 00:52:26.900
about it, people tell me that.

00:52:32.690 --> 00:52:35.160
We have some examples in
our handbook specifically

00:52:35.160 --> 00:52:37.680
that talks about some choices
that certain companies have

00:52:37.680 --> 00:52:39.420
made.

00:52:39.420 --> 00:52:42.810
I think that the
employee programs

00:52:42.810 --> 00:52:49.560
that they have at Keen IO that
were developed by Dr. Jennifer

00:52:49.560 --> 00:52:52.812
Akullian, who is one of
our board members, really,

00:52:52.812 --> 00:52:55.020
really significant and cool
stuff that they're doing,

00:52:55.020 --> 00:52:58.680
essentially a coaching
program for everybody--

00:52:58.680 --> 00:52:59.660
really cool stuff.

00:52:59.660 --> 00:53:01.530
And so it's not just
mental health stuff,

00:53:01.530 --> 00:53:03.220
but it's also like--

00:53:03.220 --> 00:53:06.120
God, I hate this
term-- life coaching.

00:53:06.120 --> 00:53:10.350
But let's imagine that
it's not as weird as it is.

00:53:10.350 --> 00:53:13.034
So stuff like that I
think is really helpful.

00:53:13.034 --> 00:53:14.325
There's a company called Olark.

00:53:17.370 --> 00:53:20.340
One of the key things that
they do, and also Keen

00:53:20.340 --> 00:53:24.421
does, is that they,
in the absence of--

00:53:24.421 --> 00:53:25.670
let me step back for a second.

00:53:25.670 --> 00:53:29.100
In the absence of
actively telling people

00:53:29.100 --> 00:53:31.620
it's OK to talk about this
stuff and to seek help,

00:53:31.620 --> 00:53:34.340
the default in our culture
is going to be a negative.

00:53:34.340 --> 00:53:35.760
The default is
going to be people

00:53:35.760 --> 00:53:37.290
falling back and
assuming that they

00:53:37.290 --> 00:53:39.670
can't talk about it safely.

00:53:39.670 --> 00:53:43.300
So companies must
actively inform

00:53:43.300 --> 00:53:46.510
about the resources they have
and about the values that they

00:53:46.510 --> 00:53:49.120
have that this is OK to discuss.

00:53:49.120 --> 00:53:51.550
So that means you can't
just put it in a handbook

00:53:51.550 --> 00:53:53.739
that somebody gets when
they start their employment

00:53:53.739 --> 00:53:55.780
and then throw it in their
desk and they're never

00:53:55.780 --> 00:53:57.070
going to look at it again.

00:53:57.070 --> 00:54:00.880
You have to actively remind
people again and again,

00:54:00.880 --> 00:54:03.976
via multiple ways
of communicating,

00:54:03.976 --> 00:54:05.350
that this is
something that's OK,

00:54:05.350 --> 00:54:08.650
that our values at this
organization are such.

00:54:08.650 --> 00:54:09.532
You must do that.

00:54:09.532 --> 00:54:10.990
And the companies
I think have been

00:54:10.990 --> 00:54:13.810
most effective at dealing with
that have been companies that

00:54:13.810 --> 00:54:16.810
make that part of their values
and their DNA, their culture,

00:54:16.810 --> 00:54:19.630
all the time, that
this is just as

00:54:19.630 --> 00:54:21.564
important as every
other health aspect.

00:54:21.564 --> 00:54:23.230
And we are going to
talk openly about it

00:54:23.230 --> 00:54:25.040
and we are going to
actively remind you

00:54:25.040 --> 00:54:27.040
that these are the resources
that are available.

00:54:27.040 --> 00:54:29.560
And that yes, you
can take a day off.

00:54:29.560 --> 00:54:33.670
Reminder, you can take a day
off if you are feeling down

00:54:33.670 --> 00:54:36.640
or stressed out or really
anxious or things like that.

00:54:36.640 --> 00:54:38.110
You can do that, and that's OK.

00:54:38.110 --> 00:54:39.910
And that's just as
valid as if you're sick

00:54:39.910 --> 00:54:41.743
or you hurt your back
or anything like that.

00:54:41.743 --> 00:54:43.660
It means you're not well
and you can do that.

00:54:43.660 --> 00:54:45.040
And that is perfectly valid.

00:54:45.040 --> 00:54:47.980
But people need to be
actively reminded of that.

00:54:47.980 --> 00:54:50.560
I think that that's a key thing.

